rnalist Andrew Brown wins 2009 Orwell book prize","webPublicationDate":"2009-04-22T18:50:00Z","sectionName":"Books","sectionId":"books","id":"books/2009/apr/22/orwell-prize-fishing-sweden","fields":{"secureThumbnail":"https://static-secure.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Books/Pix/pictures/2009/4/22/1240415443368/Andrew-Brown-004.jpg","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/274ge","standfirst":"Andrew Brown's Fishing in Utopia 'entrances' judges of Britain's pre-eminent award for political writing","hasStoryPackage":"false","lastModified":"2009-04-22T18:50:00Z","body":"<p>Guardian journalist <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/andrewbrown\" title=\"\">Andrew Brown</a> has won the Orwell book prize for his gentle evocation of his love for Sweden, Fishing in Utopia.</p><p></p><p>Brown, editor of <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/commentisfree/belief\" title=\"\">the Belief section of the Guardian's Comment is Free</a>, was presented with the £3,000 award – Britain's most prestigious for political writing – this evening at a ceremony in London. Fishing in Utopia was selected from a hugely eclectic shortlist which also included Hsiao-Hung Pai's undercover investigation into the lives of Chinese immigrants in Britain, Chinese Whispers, and Rashid Ahmed's examination of Islamic extremism, Descent Into Chaos.</p><p></p><p>\"We were simply all entranced by it. I can't put it any differently than that,\" said former Downing Street adviser and TLS editor Ferdinand Mount, who was one of this year's judges alongside author Geoffrey Wheatcroft, former editor of Granta Ian Jack and chair of the Heritage Lottery Fund Jenny Abramsky.</p><p></p><p>Fishing in Utopia is both a memoir of Brown's own life in Sweden – he lived there as a child, married a Swedish woman, worked in a timber mill and raised his own son in the country – and an exploration of the country's social and political system. Judges called it \"charming and crystalline\", and \"in its light and easy way ... as profound as it is enchanting\".</p><p></p><p>\"As well as being a marvellous book in itself, it does make you reflect on how hard it was for Sweden to transform itself into an industrial state,\" said Mount.</p><p></p><p>Detailing how Brown falls in love with Sweden, with its socialism and its fishing, and also exploring how the country loses some of its idealism as it becomes an industrial nation, Mount said that Fishing in Utopia had absolutely achieved George Orwell's ambition \"to make political writing into an art\".</p><p></p><p>\"There are many different ways of doing that,\" Mount said. \"Orwell himself chose many different forms of writing about the political scene. Chinese Whispers is in the tradition of Down and Out in Paris and London – going undercover and seeing what it's really like. Tony Judt's essay collection Reappraisals is in another tradition of Orwell – the long reflective essay on the issues of the day.\"</p><p></p><p>Mount said that Fishing in Utopia had been the unanimous choice for judges  with Mark Thompson's account of the Italian front during the first world war, The White War, coming in a narrow second.</p><p></p><p>Judt's Reappraisals, spanning the post-cold war period he terms \"the years the locusts ate\", was also a strong contender, but judges felt that Judt's work as a whole deserved special recognition and decided instead to bestow a prize for lifetime achievement on the acclaimed historian. Author of works including Postwar, a hugely acclaimed history of Europe since 1945, Judt is a \"politicologue\" and controversialist, said the judges, whose writing is distinguished by its \"intelligence, insight and conspicuous courage\".</p><p></p><p>\"If there is - in the best sense - an 'Orwellian' writer in our time, it's Tony Judt, and it is an honour to bestow honour upon him,\" they said. \"Although sometimes overshadowed by fiction and poetry, history and the essay are just as much branches of literature, and indeed of 'creative writing', and they have produced much of the best writing of our age. Even in a rich field of brilliant historians, the name of Tony Judt stands out.\"</p><p></p><p>Middle East correspondent Patrick Cockburn won the Orwell journalism prize for articles from the London Review of Books and The Independent. His book, Muqtada al-Sadr and the Fall of Iraq, had been longlisted for this year's book prize.</p>","headline":"Guardian journalist wins Orwell book prize","trailText":"Andrew Brown's Fishing in Utopia 'entrances' judges of Britain's pre-eminent award for political writing","shouldHideAdverts":"false","publication":"theguardian.com","showInRelatedContent":"true","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Books/Pix/pictures/2009/4/22/1240415443368/Andrew-Brown-004.jpg","wordcount":"578","commentable":"false","internalContentCode":"346313457","allowUgc":"false","internalOctopusCode":"1925306","isPremoderated":"false","byline":"Alison Flood","internalPageCode":"1204025","productionOffice":"UK","liveBloggingNow":"false","commentCloseDate":"2009-04-25T18:50:00Z"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2009/apr/22/orwell-prize-fishing-sweden","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/books/2009/apr/22/orwell-prize-fishing-sweden","tags":[{"id":"books/orwellprize","webTitle":"Orwell prize","type":"keyword","sectionId":"books","sectionName":"Books","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/orwellprize","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/books/orwellprize","references":[]},{"id":"culture/awards-and-prizes","webTitle":"Awards and prizes","type":"keyword","sectionId":"culture","sectionName":"Culture","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/culture/awards-and-prizes","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/culture/awards-and-prizes","references":[]},{"id":"books/politics","webTitle":"Politics","type":"keyword","sectionId":"books","sectionName":"Books","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/politics","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/books/politics","r