today the novelist and poet Helen Dunmore took a step into rather different award territory after her fictional recreation of 1952 Leningrad under Stalin, The Betrayal, was shortlisted for the Orwell book prize for political writing.</p><p></p><p>Only one novel has ever won the £3,000 Orwell book award before: Delia Jarrett-Macauley's debut Moses, Citizen and Me, a story of child soldiers in Sierra Leone, which took the prize in 2006. Dunmore's The Betrayal is the first novel on the shortlist since Marina Lewycka's Two Caravans in 2008. A sequel to The Siege, The Betrayal tells the story of a young doctor and a nursery school teacher in Leningrad, as they struggle to avoid the authorities' attention.</p><p></p><p>It was selected by judges from a longlist of 18 titles, alongside Christopher Hitchens's memoir Hitch-22, the late judge Tom Bingham's examination of law The Rule of Law, journalist Oliver Bullough's history of the people of the Caucasus mountains Let Our Fame Be Great and DR Thorpe's life of Harold Macmillan, Supermac.</p><p></p><p>An eyewitness account of the 2009 Iranian election, Death to the Dictator! written by the pseudonymous Afsaneh Moqadam, was also shortlisted for the award. The author wrote the book under a pseudonym to protect their identity, having both witnessed and participated in many of the events the book describes.</p><p></p><p>\"There is a recurrent theme in this year's books, and it is very Orwellian: fear,\" said director of the prize Jean Seaton. \"For the first time we have had to seek to preserve the anonymity of an author, Afsaneh Moqadam on Iran, and from Dunmore's gripping novel about life in Stalin's Russia to Oliver Bullough on a previously unknown genocide, the horror of authoritarian power is displayed.\"</p><p></p><p>But Seaton said there was also an answering theme \"that cherishes the individual\" in this year's final selection of titles, \"from Tom Bingham's Rule of Law which lays out (for all societies) how law, not just written down but in practice, preserves liberty and order, to Thorpe's wonderfully humane biography of Macmillan, seamlessly weaving the personal and the affairs of state, to Christopher Hitchens's grand memoir, full of brilliant writing and sharp judgments brimming with a very particular life\".</p><p></p><p>The winner of the £3,000 award will be announced on 17 May, selected by a panel of judges that features Today presenter James Naughtie, Virago Press founder Ursula Owen and Observer books editor Will Skidelsky.</p><p></p><p>The Orwell prize 2011 shortlist:</p><p>The Rule of Law by Tom Bingham</p><p>Let Our Fame Be Great: Journeys Among the Defiant People of the Caucasus by Oliver Bullough</p><p>The Betrayal by Helen Dunmore</p><p>Hitch-22 by Christopher Hitchens</p><p>Death to the Dictator! by Afsaneh Moqadam</p><p>Supermac: The Life of Harold MacMillan by DR Thorpe</p>","headline":"Helen Dunmore novel shortlisted for Orwell prize","trailText":"Booker-nominated recreation of Stalinist Russia, The Betrayal, is finalist for political writing award <br />","shouldHideAdverts":"false","publication":"theguardian.com","showInRelatedContent":"true","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/BOOKS/Pix/pictures/2011/4/26/1303831523043/Helen-Dunmore-003.jpg","wordcount":"449","commentable":"true","internalContentCode":"373990373","allowUgc":"false","internalOctopusCode":"4629538","isPremoderated":"false","byline":"Alison Flood","internalPageCode":"1550341","productionOffice":"UK","liveBloggingNow":"false","commentCloseDate":"2011-04-29T18:30:01Z"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2011/apr/26/helen-dunmore-orwell-prize","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/books/2011/apr/26/helen-dunmore-orwell-prize","tags":[{"id":"books/orwellprize","webTitle":"Orwell prize","type":"keyword","sectionId":"books","sectionName":"Books","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/orwellprize","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/books/orwellprize","refer